ually outputs \"gen01\" (because of swap 1). So sumGate found, but output is gen01 not z01. We detect z01<->gen01 swap and repair. carry01 gets computed correctly.\n- Bit 2: XOR(x02,y02)->tmp02. XOR(tmp02,carry01)->z02 (correct). AND(x02,y02)->gen02, AND(tmp02,carry01)->z03 (was prop02). OR(gen02,z03) should give carry. But we're looking for OR(gen02.out, propGate.out). propGate = AND(tmp02,carry01) which outputs z03. So OR(gen02, z03)... this outputs \"tmp03\" (the OR gate at bit2 was carry02 which was swapped to tmp03). So carry = tmp03.\n- Bit 3: XOR(x03,y03) outputs \"carry02\". So tmp=carry02. XOR(carry02, tmp03)... this is the gate that outputs \"prop02\" (was z03, swapped). So sumGate is found. But output is prop02, should be z03. We detect prop02<->z03 swap and repair.\n\nBut we NEVER detect:\n- carry02 <-> tmp03 (swap 3)\n\nBecause at bit 2, the OR gate correctly computes gen02 OR prop02, but its output is \"tmp03\" (after the swap). At bit 3, the XOR(x03,y03) outputs \"carry02\". Then XOR(carry02, tmp03) is found because those ARE the correct wire names post-swap, and the gate is found with those inputs. So the structural walk doesn't detect that carry02 and tmp03 are swapped because the swap is between \"adjacent\" stages and the names flow through consistently.\n\nThe question: what structural rule can I apply to detect this? The key insight is that the carry wire from bit N should NOT be the output of a gate that takes xNN+1/yNN+1 as input. Similarly, the tmp wire for bit N should NOT be the output of an OR gate.\n\nCan you help me think through what additional structural checks would catch ALL types of swaps? I need to identify when:\n1. A carry wire (output of OR gate) was swapped with a tmp wire (output of XOR with x/y inputs)  \n2. Any other \"role mismatch\" between gates\n\nPlease reason about this carefully and give me a concrete algorithm that handles all swap types.","agentId":"aa31fc8","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Everything is clean and 